# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
First, think from the smallest part. The smallest part or the base case of a tree to consider is when it is null.

- If both trees are null, they are the same. So, we will return true.
- If one of them is null, then they cannot be equal. So, we will return false.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a0233f35-a325-4a35-84d2-6ce2767a81dc_1673326587.6208208.png)

- When both nodes are not null, we first need to check if the values are equal. Then we will traverse the left subtree and the right subtree of the both tree sequentially.

- Check if `p.val == q.val`:

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7c934401-4552-40ff-8b3c-d1ad64758202_1673326852.0365388.png)

- Recursively call the left and right subtree:

- Left Subtree `isSameTree(p.left, q.left)` :

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a359591a-bcf4-4b46-8e47-3ee1d7c598cc_1673326981.6579647.png)

- Right Subtree `isSameTree(p.right, q.right)` :

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/5e6e7bfb-a2e2-4114-8085-9175430c08de_1673327073.0911453.png)


- Now, all of these must return true. So, the recursive call should return:

`p.val == q.val && isSameTree(p.left, q.left) && isSameTree(p.right, q.right)`

If one of them is not true, it will be false. That's why we need the && operation.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
As we visit every node of the tree.

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The recursion stack is called n times in worst case. So, it will need $$O(n)$$ memory.

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public boolean isSameTree(TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        if(p == null && q == null){
            return true;
        }
        if(p == null || q == null){
            return false;
        }
        return p.val == q.val && isSameTree(p.left, q.left) && isSameTree(p.right, q.right);
    }
}
```

