### Approach 1 - DFS
We have to perform DFS on both the trees simultaneously and at any point if the value is not same we can return false
1. If p or q is null - IF both are null return true otherwise return false
2. Both are non-null so if p->val != q->val, return false
3. perform DFS on left and right children and return true only if both are true otherwise return false (left && right);
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isSameTree(TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
        if(!p || !q) return p == q; 
        if(p->val != q->val) return false;
        return isSameTree(p->left,q->left) && isSameTree(p->right,q->right);
    }
};
```

### Approach 2 - BFS (level order traversal)
We will use a queue for this purpose
1. Check if the initial p and q are valid. If not return false.
2. insert them in the queue - qu (pair - {p,q})
3. while qu is not empty (qu is empty - last level)
4. store the current size of q in sz - the elements we have to check in current level
5. Perform the checks if both are valid. If not return false.
6. If both are valid insert their left and right children as pair in the queue
7. Perform the same operation using loop for the level then we go to next level and so on
8. If the entire tree is valid the loop ends and return true;
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isSameTree(TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
        if(!p || !q) return p == q;
        if(p->val != q->val) return false;
        queue<pair<TreeNode*,TreeNode*>> qu;
        qu.push({p,q});
        while(!qu.empty()){
            int sz = qu.size();
            while(sz--){
                auto pu = qu.front();qu.pop();           
                if((!pu.first || !pu.second) && (pu.first != pu.second))  return false;
                if(!pu.first && !pu.second) continue;
                if(pu.first->val != pu.second->val) return false;
                qu.push({pu.first->left,pu.second->left});
                qu.push({pu.first->right,pu.second->right});
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
};
```

