# Intuition 💡
To determine if two binary trees are the same, we can compare their nodes recursively. If the current nodes have the same value and the left and right subtrees are also the same, then the trees are considered the same.

# Approach 🔍
Here is the step-by-step approach to solve the problem:

1. Write a recursive function `isSameTree` that takes two parameters, `p` and `q`, representing the root nodes of the two binary trees.
2. Check if either `p` or `q` is null. If one is null and the other is not, return false since they cannot be the same.
3. Check if the values of the current nodes, `p.val` and `q.val`, are equal.
4. Recursively call the `isSameTree` function on the left subtrees, `p.left` and `q.left`.
5. Recursively call the `isSameTree` function on the right subtrees, `p.right` and `q.right`.
6. Return the logical AND of all the conditions checked above.

> Feel free to post your doubts in the commen section :) 
# Code 
The Java code implementing the above approach is as follows:

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isSameTree(TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {

        if (p == null || q == null) { return p == q;}

        return (p.val == q.val) && isSameTree(p.left, q.left) && isSameTree(p.right, q.right); 
    }
}```

