Explanations:
Method 1: Our own and powerful DFS, we just go to every one, from there travel
to its every adjacent 1, and mark it as zero.
Now for one island one dfs will mark all of its adjacent 1s to zero. 
Another 1 comes, that means one more island or component to work with and we travel from that 1, 
to all of its adjacent and mark it as zero.

Method 2: Basic BFS, We encounter a 1, we do bfs from that one to all its adjacent 1's 
just like we did in our DFS, the method is different, here we use a que, insert adjacent 1, and keep doing it.

Method 3: Union Find, Here we are only doing Path Compression and not Union, 
which only hampers our time complexity by a constant but we do save space
because we didn't take a size array nor did we make an extra class. 
And more over this method is simpler to code in actual interview sense.
So, what we did was first declare every element to be its own parent.
Now, we encounter our (name: hero)first one, its parent is him only,
then we go to its adjacent elements and mark its parent as the 
index of our first one(remember, hero) only. 
After we our done with this process, we just go and traverse all the elements which
are its own parent and in grid its value is '1'.
Simple, and codeable in an interview. 
