solutions.content:
**PROBLEM STATEMENT**
//this problem is similar to that of number of components in an undirected graph.
//our task is to return number of connected components (which are islands indirectly in this problem)
//The islands are denoted with '1' and water with '0'.
**APPROACH**
-> we will use a seperate function which will perform DFS traversal 
->  we will mark the visited vertex as '0' (can mark it as any other number also)
-> In our main function , we will traverse every row and every column and check if it is not visited 
->if it is not visited then we will perform the traversal and increment the count 'n' which will store no of times the DFS traversal is performed 
-> no of times DFS performed = no of islands (connected components)

**CODE**
```
int numIslands(vector<vector<char>>& grid) {
        //to check 
        int n = 0;//islands count
        for(int i=0;i< grid.size();i++){
            for(int j=0;j< grid[0].size();j++){
                //performing DFS if its not visited
                if(grid[i][j]=='1'){
                    n++;
                    DFS(i,j,grid);
                }
            }
        }
        return n;
    }
    void DFS(int r,int c,vector<vector<char>>& grid){
        //preventing crossing boundaries by checking
        if(r<0 || r>=grid.size() || c<0 || c>=grid[0].size()){
            return;
        }
        //returning if the cuRrent position is already visited
        if(grid[r][c]=='0'){
            return;
        }
        //marking the unvisited vertex as visited by marking it as 0
        grid[r][c] = '0';
        //moving in all 4 directions and visiting them recursively
        DFS(r+1,c,grid);
        DFS(r,c-1,grid);
        DFS(r-1,c,grid);
        DFS(r,c+1,grid);
    }

```
