Solution 1, Dynamic programming
In this solution we initialize a dp array

For this solution, and each index i, 
if the current value `nums[i]` is greater than the previous value, `nums[j]` (since we index i from 1, and j from 0)
	We have to ask ourselves, is the current state `dp[i]`, greater than the previous letter's state, plus the current character, hence `dp[j]+1`

```
	var lengthOfLIS = function(nums){
		const dp = Array(nums.length).fill(1);
		let max = 1;
		for(let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++){
			for(let = j = 1; j < i; j++){
				if(nums[i] > nums[j]){
					dp[i] = Math.max(dp[i], dp[j]+1);
					max = Math.max(dp[i], max);
				}
			}
		}
		return max
	}
```

Solution 2, intelligent substring building
While the first solution requires us to loop from 0, to less than i in the `nums` array, this solution will require us to loop from inside the substring that we are building. 
We don't need to initalize a dp array, however we will have a an array called `sub`

```
var lengthOfLIS = function(nums) {
    // implementing solution 2
    let sub = [nums[0]]; 
    for(let i = 1; i< nums.length; i++){
        let currVal = nums[i]; 
		// important, this is from sub
        let prevVal = sub[i-1];
        if(currVal > prevVal){
            // meaning there is increasing
            // because prevVal is < currVal
            // push into subsequence array
            sub.push(currVal)
        } else {
            // currVal is smaller than previous
            // so this is not a continously increasing value
            // check from the beginning of our sub array
            let j = 0; 
            while(currVal > sub[j]){
                j++;
            }
            sub[j] = currVal;
        }

    }
    return sub.length
};
```

