# Explanation.
TreeSet.ceiling return the leatest element greater than or equal to X, or null if there is no such element. 
On every step we add a new value to our set, but before remove the greatest to current. With this approach out set contains the longest subsequence on every step, and as a result at the end size of set is out goal.

# Complexity. 
**O(N  * logN)**, because we find the greater in the tree for every n of the numbers at each step.
*TreeSet.ceiling() ::= O(logN)*, because *logN* is a height of the tree

```
class Solution {
    public int lengthOfLIS(int[] nums) {
        var set = new TreeSet<Integer>();
        for (var i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            var currElem = set.ceiling(nums[i]); 
            if (currElem != null) {
                set.remove(currElem);
            }
            set.add(nums[i]);
        }
        return set.size();
    }
}
```

