solutions.content:
This is a classic Dynamic Programming question. We saw different DP solutions posted in Discuss section. To understand those solutions, it is important to get clear -- What does that `int[] dp` store?

Personally, I think it is more important to understand the O(n^2) solution than memorizing the Binary Search O(nlogn) solution, because the standard DP solution can be used to resolve many other DP questinos. 

Textbook DP Solution
```
class Solution {
    public int lengthOfLIS(int[] nums) {
        if (nums.length == 0) return 0; 
        int[] dp = new int[nums.length]; 
        Arrays.fill(dp, 1);  // For each element in nums, by default the length of LIS is 1. i.e. nums = [1], return 1. 

        for (int j = 1; j < nums.length; j++) { // j represents where we currently stand at. No need to check j = 0 case, dp array is already filled with 1
            for (int i = 0; i < j; i++) { // i loops through all the elements from 0 to j, so i starts from 0
                if (nums[j] > nums[i]) { // only if nums[j] > nums[i] could we append nums[j] to nums[i] to form a longer sequence 
                    dp[j] = Math.max(dp[j], dp[i] + 1);  // which one is longer for dp[j]? previously calculated dp[i] or dp[j] append to the current nums[i]?
                }
            }
        }

        int finalmax = 0; 

        /* Why dp[dp.length - 1] is not the correct answer? 
           because this dp array stores the value of "if append nums[j], what would the longest length be", not "the longest length so for at nums[j]"
           so we need to loop through the whole dp array to find out the largest number */
        for (int i = 0; i < dp.length; i++) {
            finalmax = Math.max(finalmax, dp[i]); 
        }

        return finalmax; 
    }
}
```

What if we would like to avoid looping through dp array? Yes, it can be done. 
```
class Solution {
    public int lengthOfLIS(int[] nums) {
        if (nums.length == 0) return 0; 
        int[] dp = new int[nums.length]; 
        Arrays.fill(dp, 1); 
        int finalmax = 1; 

        for (int j = 1; j < nums.length; j++) {
            for (int i = 0; i < j; i++) { 
                if (nums[j] > nums[i]) { 
                    dp[j] = Math.max(dp[j], dp[i] + 1);  
                    finalmax = Math.max(finalmax, dp[j]); // update finalmax every time dp[j] is updated, to avoid looping through dp array later
                }
            }
        }

        return finalmax; 
    }
}
```
