**Intuition for DP question.** 
1) We can see there can be n number of subsequences. So recursion is the way.
2) Then question is asking for Longest ( which is the optimal ask) so DP. 

**Understanding Recursion**

- The question breaks down to a very familiar pattern of choose/not-choose. So keeping that in mind and following the question's restriction which is **longest strictly increasing subsequence**
- If the condition is not valid i.e, the nums[index+1]th value is not greater to nums[index] then just move forward without choosing and also without increasing our count. 
- Other part comes if the condition is actually valid. Even then we can have two options to choose or not choose. WHY? Consider this example [0,1,0,3,2,3], here we can have multiple subsequences [0,1,3], [0,1,2,3] and so on. 

``` class Solution {
    int count1, count2;
    public int lengthOfLIS(int[] nums) {

        return recursion(nums, 0, Integer.MIN_VALUE);
    }

    int recursion(int[] nums, int index, int prev) {
	// prev parameter we will be using to keep value of (index-1)th element
        if(index >= nums.length) return 0;

        if(nums[index] > prev) { /* when the condition matches either choose or not choose
		while choosing increase the count and change the prev to current value */
            return Math.max(1 + recursion( nums, index + 1, nums[index]), recursion(nums, index + 1, prev));
        }
        /* If the condition does not match then just move forward without choosing */
        return recursion(nums, index + 1, prev);

    }

	This will give TLE. So we need to memoize this code ->DP bottom up -> check for any space optimization if possible.

